<h2>The Practical Path</h2>

<p>How does a person pursue theosis? The Eastern tradition is quite practical about this. The path consists of:</p>

<p><strong>The sacraments</strong> — especially the Eucharist, regularly received. This is the primary vehicle of theosis, the "medicine of immortality."</p>

<p><strong>Prayer</strong> — daily, structured, persistent. The Jesus Prayer is the backbone, but the tradition includes morning and evening prayers, the Psalms, and liturgical worship.</p>

<p><strong>Fasting</strong> — not as punishment but as training. Fasting teaches the body that it is not in charge, creating space for the spirit to grow.</p>

<p><strong>Repentance and confession</strong> — the regular diagnosis and treatment of spiritual illness. Not a one-time event but a lifelong habit.</p>

<p><strong>Community</strong> — theosis does not happen in isolation. It happens in the Church, in relationship with other struggling, growing Christians.</p>

<p>Theosis is not a destination you arrive at. It is a direction you move in — and the Eastern Church believes that every human being, in every circumstance, is invited to begin.</p>

